The first virtual provider is already coming to Czechia this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait for a long time.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers work to the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on mobile.cz.
This also confirmed the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for a SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, there is as likely a paradoxic situation - for some customers of Czech mobile phone providers, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
Why are the prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it is lacking the competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators are happy to shrink that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) also often joins Pavel Dvořák, who in the past often expressed that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classical provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (usually he would hardly find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of virtual providers to the mobile phone market led to a significant reduction in the price, which then had to respond to the classic mobile providers.
There were similar votes in the UK before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has shown that there is space for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you do not need to look for examples for a long time.
In February this we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers, thus rising up to the country's five largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group of Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
To be able to work effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, but often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite good to put on a non-cashing target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take foot in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory from the view of the service provision."
In Czechia chanceless, the mobile providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers Czechia, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem particularly hopeful.
There will be a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly appreciative to this thought.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything for the lack of a potential competitor.
Your interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider has been showing GTS Novera group who wants to take a further step in order to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-net but also mobile telecom services.
And the earlier, the better.
On this possibility we have repeatedly negotiated with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," says the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But until now this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"In this moment, we do not assume that there is space for a full-value virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
To date, we have not yet addressed a subject with a complex and serious project in this area," says in his explanation for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónica O2 press department.
Further suppliers also point to the Czech market specific.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare harmony with the O2 declaration: "We have not yet found a viable and both-sided beneficial project to build on."
And she adds: "The network of T-Mobile will hardly appear a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment we should have already had a specific offer to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses on fulfilling the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open for negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of dividing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we consider from the view of customers to be the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The action of mobile phone providers is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why should such competitors facilitate entry into the market?
The fact that the providers can draw on a strain when it comes to something, is also the long back and down about the origin of U:fon.
The strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the time when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also demonstrates publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition environment of the mobile phone market has recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is evident that a new player on the market itself and above all its services would require high demands."
However, in view of this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which is unfortunately in the Czech Republic, in contrast to the UK and other highly developed countries, that is not the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem as its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
Until now no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical providers," said in his reply to our request Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS Department of External Relations.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by representatives of the providers.
This is more than vulnerable from an authority that is to represent consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one misuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Where virtual providers work normally abroad, it is to be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a lower price in mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a lowering of prices is probably not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
