Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her founding, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had all reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most safe and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, she regained the public's confidence, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian red cross were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the Government of Canada in February 1994 initiated a public investigation conducted by Judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light into the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and drafting directives to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever still hesitated to submit his report, several provinces at that time put a committee on the legs whose aim was to develop a new system for the management of blood conservation in Canada.
In Quebec, the Committee of Gélineau completed this order.
According to the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were founded in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society, to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec took up her work, almost 38% of people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
With the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood conservation and through work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence before proudly emphasizes that in early 2008 almost 94% of Quebec’s trust in Hema-Quebec was now in the midst of 2008.
Dr. Décary, however, maintains in consciousness that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on 28 September 1998 Hema-Quebec acts according to the principle of caution.
At this time, we have experienced the emergence of numerous cases of human form of bovine maleness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been headed since the founding of 1998.
And we did not have the least idea whether this disease could be transferred over blood.
So we called on one of the main directives of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which, as a result of exclusion measures, if we do not know this and if a disease is slowly progressing, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had stopped in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it has been proved that this disease is transferred over blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique to detect HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable it to demonstrate the virus’s presence directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the previously used tests.
The NST enabled it to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be demonstrated by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognise this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one of 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, this means that 12 million blood conservations should be distributed before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributed between 400.000 and 500.000 blood conservations each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transferred over a blood conservation.
I believe you can feel comfortable today when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore your health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what disease agents can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus has appeared on the island of Réunion, which is transmitted through insects through the blood, just like the West Nile virus.
We have to monitor continuously," continues Dr. Décary before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec, in addition to a safe supply, also needs to provide adequate supply.
`The need increases because the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or blood plates.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, of which, on average, only 3% of Quebec's blood donated inhabitants are.'
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they are sick of AIDS or malaria, and whoever traveled to a country where malaria is spread is excluded from the donation of blood for a year.
`With this 3% we create an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
No stocks are very rare.
But you need to renew the members of this donor network when they grow older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and to bring them to become regular donors.
Nowadays, life is so hectic that one seldom finds time to spend an hour in the donation of blood," regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood conservations but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are almost exclusively used in heavy burning injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public navel navel blood bank of Quebec.
The navel snail, which was previously considered biomedical waste, is rich in stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases, such as leukemia.
`A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth navel snail blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand annually.
`We should probably begin to make it available for transplants at the beginning of the next year', explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of navel blood loss as very popular.
`Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
