The psychology of the overboy - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus to overview the security bidder.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now been able to discover the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves in a competition, such as a auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play lotto, while the other participated in a gambling action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain ring, was measured in losers of the auction, which plays an essential role in offering the opponent.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that price increase was explained by avoiding an overreaction of the Striatum.
In order to undermine their thesis, the economists in the research group have further studied the follow-up of money.
In this case, three groups should offer against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
In addition, another group was promised 15 dollars reward, in the case that they come out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore merely that the emphasis on the one was on the win, while the other was on the loss.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologians, however, the members of the "contrary to losing" group were ready to make higher interventions than those in the control or "winn" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
They have so far just reasoned the practices observed in auctions with the joy of gaining or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was dissolved thanks to the illustrative neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation parat" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the economic faculty of the University of New York.
