Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed under the leading causes of death.
The number of infected persons is estimated to be hundreds of thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective concept for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellow insufficiency are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Depending on the pathogens, hepatitis viruses spread to two different types: in hepatitis A and E, the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body liquids (e.g. sperm, secret or speal).
Travelers are advised to vaccinate the virus A and B, in any case, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show about two-third weeks after the consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by inconvenience, weakness, abdominal pain and breeding.
Afterwards the yellow addiction occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery may last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the diseases caused by hepatitis B, much more severe, such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
