Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the ignorance destructions the liver cells in secretly - in many cases the first symptoms are shown after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more frequent: those undergoing blood transfusion before 1991, drug dependents, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C diseases is estimated to be 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already proven in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the doctor in the first signs of unknown origin.
Right-time recognized, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, which banns the risk of infection and prevents the emergence of cancer.
