The combined eye of the bee, which can see in every direction and in an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a 180-degree face area within 2 meters, calculates its distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately initiates the collisions avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in seconds, and the authorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tyres around the corresponding angle.
This manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively, unlike systems before.
"If not, the authorobot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the authorobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innerest and most vulnerable part of the protective shield - a layer within the accidents currently considered inevitable.
The entire process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that must be in the fraction of a second.
However, retirement, unlike the bees, cannot be up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, in the direction of the tyres.
While the bees here are infinitely open to avoid other bees, researchers were able to operate only the rotary movement, or acceleration and abbreviation.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and less to the ability to store it.
This device must only process some inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It doesn't have to save it, or create an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of former manövers, so it's still using just a handful of KB Memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collisions prevention technology, which, according to Nissan's assessment, will be serial in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
