The historical cinemas are closed due to the beneficiary multiplexkinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the great multi-sale complex in the periphery, in the long term means death for the indoor cinema in the center. A process that appears not only inevitable and irreversible, but also the trains of a cultural crime.
Most of the historical locations are full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with which one put down a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which brought him in 20 years ago the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes. It's the history of a suburb cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a well lost cinema world.
The figures that the Anec, the central commercial association, provides, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the huge amount of 316 traditional cinemas have to be closed; these cinemas mostly paid the cinemas in the large cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main guilty are the multiplexkinos, because it is just these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has made the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and the Emilia-Romagna.
