In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be necessary."
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to fears about the old cinemas, has decided to protect them by an agreement between the community and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy that aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The proposed measures also include tax advantages for the cinema drivers and benefits for the public regarding transport: it will be allowed to drive to the areas of the centre and park on cheaper parking fees.
"It is a delightful initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also create new concepts.
